    "location": "Dim sum restaurant, Jordan",
    "context": "Yum cha (飲茶) on Sunday morning is a Hong Kong institution. Whole families gather — three generations at one table is normal. You order from a checklist sheet or flag down the trolley lady and shout what you want.",
    "cultural_note": "When someone refills your tea at a yum cha table, the correct response is to tap two bent fingers on the table. Legend traces the gesture to the Qianlong Emperor, who travelled incognito and poured tea for his companions; unable to kowtow without revealing him, they tapped bent fingers to mimic a kneeling bow. Every dim sum table in Hong Kong is quietly re-enacting that story.",
